President Obama has named seventeen recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor. The award recognizes individuals who have made significant contributions to the United States' security, national interests, world peace, or cultural endeavors. The recipients include Yogi Berra, a legendary baseball player; Bonnie Carroll, a military and veterans advocate; Shirley Chisholm, the first African-American woman elected to Congress; Emilio and Gloria Estefan, influential music artists; Billy Frank Jr., an advocate for Indian treaty rights and environmental stewardship; Lee Hamilton, a former Congressman and influential voice on international relations; Katherine G. Johnson, a pioneering NASA mathematician; Willie Mays, a professional baseball player; Barbara Mikulski, the longest-serving female Senator; Itzhak Perlman, a renowned violinist and conductor; William Ruckelshaus, former EPA Administrator and public health advocate; Stephen Sondheim, a influential theater composer and lyricist; Steven Spielberg, a prominent filmmaker and philanthropist; Barbra Streisand, a multi-talented performer and advocate; James Taylor, a singer-songwriter; and Minoru Yasui, a civil and human rights leader. The awards will be presented at the White House on November 24th.